 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/udaeja.showPublicProfile?language=EN>daeja</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://liquid2k.com/daeja/gem2_839.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/15/02 6:15:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1105.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hmm...</span><hr size=1> And why should one's gear have any bearing on his/her ability to RP? This makes no sense to me. Honestly, it sounds like sour grapes to me. <br>
<br>
Yes, this is a fantasy setting. Yes, this is a roleplay server. Now, to make it somewhat &quot;believeable&quot;, we need to throw some other aspects into the fold so that all of our stories do not all end up as &quot;I am an orphan - i soon find out my parents were the king/queen,.princess, heir to the throne of...etc.&quot;<br>
<br>
You don't agree with twinking. Ok.<br>
You feel strongly about and encourage/participate in roleplay. ok.<br>
<br>
Now, why is it unfathomable to see and respect the circumstances and life choices a person may have for his/her character? <br>
<br>
Some born with silver spoonsin their mouths. Others paupers. We each have a goal, or a struggle,  a love triangle or a destiny. <br>
<br>
Also, why is it not acceptable to change your career or path in life? Hell, in RL I still don't know what I want to do when I grow up, and I am in my mid 20's. I've changed my long term goals many times, simply because there is so much i want to do, and so many things I enjoy. <br>
<br>
Sarhea's story was unfolding, and the only way to display this in game  was to make a change (deleting and starting over) - this is because we are hindered by the in's and out's of what we can or can't do as a result of programming.<br>
<br>
In all honesty, many  of the people who make up the FV server have played EQ on other servers. In my opinion, those of us who have previous <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> knowledge</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of EQ are the most twinked. You know the experience quests. You know where to get the items your class needs. <br>
How many dwarves have done the bone chip quest in Kaladim for experience and patchwork? They didn't happen upon the quest by exploring. They knew of it from Everlore or any other EQ site with quest info.<br>
<br>
Many of you are deluding yourselves. Many of you are being harsh because of mob mentality. Give her a break - she's obviously a well respected RPer...hell, doesn't *that* earn her something besides this rudeness?<br>
<br>
/bow Sarhea<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ublakkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blakkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/15/02 6:39:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1105.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Jakara...</span><hr size=1> How do you know that twink is a real twink and not some lucky soul... Example I once new a player who managed to kill Pjzin in qeynos hills at  a young age... this was when Glowing black stones were worth 10000plat.   So at age 15 or so this fellow was completely decked out.  Is this a twink?<br>
<br>
How do you know that the player didnt find a marketplace and trade their way up to good gear for 3 months before adventuring.<br>
<br>
People level at varying rates, people are better or worse at trading, and in EQ sometimes you hit an early jackpot.<br>
<br>
I would be careful about knee jerk labeling, you could miss a great friendship, or roleplay opportunity. <p>Lorec <br>
Wandering Judge of the Tribunal <br>

Lousy Tailor <br>
Better Brewer <br>
Excellent Drunk <br>
Aspiring Polyglot <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umoandor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Moandor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/15/02 8:18:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1105.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Jakara...</span><hr size=1> Let's not judge people by their looks or their gear. Judge them only by their actions, their attitudes, and the words that come out of their mouths. <br>
<br>
In my former server before coming back to EQ in FV, I had a semi-rich gnome. Yes he was twinked a bit because of generous loving guildmates. But what I often did was that I dressed up as a pauper, dressed up in newbie gear, and then went anonymous. I then wandered around the newbie zone in Steamfont, looking after the true newbie gnomes. At least twice, a couple of the newbie gnomes were kind enough to stop and chat with me. I tried to pass myself off as a struggling newbie just like them. In fact, they even generously GAVE me their accumulated bone chips when I tried to pass off as a necromancer. These are the kind of players that I like. They are generous and considerate even when they have almost nothing. Trust me, I returned their kindness more than tenfold.  <br>
<br>
The lesson here is try to give people the benefit of the doubt, rather than the other way around. <br>
<br>
Things are never as they seem. Looks are always deceiving, and the looks of a person hardly is an indication of that person's real value or being.  So going back to Sarhea's original predicament, it was obviously wrong to be judgemental about her based on the gear she had. <br>
<br>
